body:
Hello,

First, thank you, Tox is a great program ! I'm using (u/q)Tox with a friend, and since a few weeks (she didn't do any update) she cannot be connected to the Tox network anymore from her flat using both uTox and qTox (the internet provider provides internet for students, I'm not aware of the network architecture, but basically she needs to authenticate from a web page in order to get internet). The strange thing is that it works elsewhere (at home), and that it worked a few month ago, so I think that the internet provider changed it's policy, or the network map... The "bug" is that utox and qtox never get connected, the (usually green) dot stay grey. So here are my questions:

- is it possible to change the port used by tox ? Maybe the internet provider choose to close the corresponding port, and it would be nice to change the port to test
- how could I debug it to know why it doesn't work anymore ? Do you have any idea ?

Thank you in advance for your help, 

tobiasBora.

comment_data.body: What is the operating system it's running on?
It's Xubuntu 16.04. Installed from the tox repositories.

Assuming you're on uTox... Can you run it from the terminal with `-vvvv` and past the output somewhere?

You may want to redact the output, as it will include your ToxID if you want that to remain private.

Yes, here is the output. She also tried with UDP/IPv6 off.

Thank you for your help !
Do you know what could be the reason of the bug ?

I don't other than to say it's being blocked by the network. 

If you're able to compile from source, I can give you an update nodes list to try (I'm just going to remove all the nodes that don't run on port 443) And see if they're just using simple packet shaping.

Yes, I think I can compile it from source. Which version should I compile ?

The nodes are on port 443 ? I don't see how the network can block this port since most website use it...

And I don't understand what you mean with "See if they're just using simple packet shaping".

The vast majority of nodes are not on port 443, that's why I'm hopeful that if you are able to compile a version of uTox with only nodes on port 443, and TCP only, it will work.

Compile the development branch of uTox https://github.com/uTox/uTox/ once you're able to compile, ping me, and I'll give you a file to replace, before you recompile.
I can compile it without any problem, I made a docker that compile & run it here: https://github.com/tobiasBora/docker-tox-git-pulseaudio. What should I do next ?

Great, thank you a lot for your help. Now I'll give that to my friend to try it, I'll let you know if it works.

Thank you !

PS: If someone wants to try it, I put the docker file in the branch "bootstrap_443" of https://github.com/tobiasBora/docker-tox-git-pulseaudio/.

Two of the mentioned nodes **104.219.184.206** and **194.249.212.109** don't work anymore (or at the moment) and I don't see **46.101.197.175** anywhere. By the way, how can the third field (the byte array) be extracted from [this node list](https://wiki.tox.chat/users/nodes)?

What is the `{0x??, 0x??, ...` part for **46.101.197.175** with public key `2555763C8C460495B14157D234DD56B86300A2395554BCAE4621AC345B8C1B1B`?
That's the public key of the node. In the hex format that toxcore needs.
Good. Thanks. I just messed up my perl script that converted it into C-style byte array and it confused me because the result was much shorter. :P

Sorry for the time I spent to give you the feedback, but indeed when I run uTox on ports 443 it works great. So if it was possible to set up a way to connect to port 443 first, or only allow only a subset of ports it would be great !

Thank you !
